ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the effects of CDs and MXenes decorated on the Composite2 electrode on the enhanced specific capacitance, the electron transfer process was examined from the CV data. Six electrode systems were investigated, including AC, NiDMR, Composite2, Composite2/10%wt CDs, Composite2/10%wt MXenes, and Composite2/5%wt CDs/5%wt MXenes. Following the Cottrell's equation (Supporting information), the logarithmic scan rate and logarithmic current were plotted (Fig. S8a). The slope of the plot is the b-value. If the b-value is 0.5, the electron transfer is the diffusion-controlled or pseudocapacitive process, whereas if the b-value is 1, the electron transfer is the surface-controlled or EDLC process [50]. If the b-value is between 0.5 and 1, it indicates a combination of surface- and diffusion-controlled processes. The AC and NiDMR electrodes had the b-values of 0.9722 and 0.7694, the typical behaviors of EDLC and pseudocapacitive materials, respectively. The Composite2 electrode gave a b-value of 0.9465, which is also a surface dominance. When the CDs were added to the system, the b-value rose to 0.9922, which is even higher than that of the pure AC electrode. It can be concluded that the CDs greatly improved the EDLC properties. In the meantime, the MXenes-decorated Composite2 electrode provided a b-value of 0.8000, meaning that the MXenes contributed to the pseudocapacitive properties. The Composite2/5%wt CDs/5%wt MXenes electrode gave a b-value of 0.9436. It again demonstrates that the AC/NiDMR composite combines the EDLC and pseudocapacitor properties, and CDs and MXenes enhanced the surface- and diffusion-controlled processes, respectively. Fig. S8b and c confirm that all systems consisted of surface and diffusion-controlled processes because the values of R2 are close to unity. To confirm this finding, the EIS results of these systems were used to evaluate the ion diffusion process. The plot between real impedance (Z′) and the inverse square root of angular frequency (ω−1/2) in the low-frequency region determined the Warburg coefficient (
                           σ
                        ) based on the Warburg impedance equation. It was found that the AC and NiDMR electrodes gave Warburg coefficients of 8.72 and 8.12 Ω s−1, respectively. Meanwhile, the Composite2 electrode yielded a Warburg coefficient of 8.52 Ω s−1 due to a combination of AC and NiDMR (Fig. S9). When the CDs were added to the Composite2 electrode, the Warburg coefficient rose to 8.70 Ω s−1, while the MXenes-added Composite2 electrode had a Warburg coefficient of 7.95 Ω s−1. The Warburg coefficient is an inverse of the diffusion coefficient, which means that the CDs in an electrode reduced the diffusion process, emphasizing the role of the CDs as surface-process enhancers, whereas the MXenes enhanced the diffusion process. The Composite2/5%wt CDs/5%wt MXenes electrode gave a Warburg coefficient of 8.40 Ω s−1, a balance between surface and diffusion processes in the electrode.
